			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Okay, I have read a majority of ideas. Listened to a majority of complaining about why this pet is broke, why this one needs to fixed, and then it hit me. 
<br />

<br />
Instead of trying to fix the pets we have. Instead of trying to boost the mitigation / DPS and any balance issues. Give us the pets that can make everyone happy.
<br />

<br />
In other words. recreate the pet based on a point system. Have it start from the very first level that we get pets. Every level we achieve we get say, 4 points to spend in any given section. (have a window that would come up much like when we go to a mage guildmaster to train for our own abilities). Only this one would appear and would show something like"
<br />

<br />
1: Attack    Skill level : 1
<br />
2: Defense   Skill level: 1
<br />
3: Proc :  magic : 1
<br />
4: Proc : fire: 1
<br />
5. proc: snare : 1
<br />
6. Proc: stun :1
<br />
7. Proc: ice : 1
<br />
8. Proc: root : 1
<br />
9. Duration of pet proc: 1
<br />
6. Taunt level: 1
<br />
7. Regen: 1
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
and many other possible options. We could have a window that would appear whenever we cast a spell to create a pet and these would appear. Much like the way we can save spell gems, we could do the same for our own Personal version of pet. Obviously, with each numberical increase, the power would increase for that given stat.
<br />

<br />
At least with this option, we could create a totally offensive pet, perfect for raids with no defensive abilities, (unless we choose), or, we could create a pet geared more towards our solo path. At any time we choose. The number 1 beside each is just a representaion on what the points would cost.
<br />

<br />
I'm sure that it would be easier for balance issues, if, by the tier levels, our pet seemed..lacking, they could just implement more points to distribute upon entering the planes to balance issues.
<br />

<br />
Loscekiax Brokeitagain</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
