			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">What you're asking for is power at the cost of specialty. For mages to be able to specialize and branch off into sub-types. For mages to be strong in some areas and weak in others. 
<br />
<p>
<br />
That ain't gonna werk 'round these parts son.
<br />
<p>
<br />
No, you'll be suprised to find that most people frown when you say "give and take" as opposed to "give and give". Sony tried to mix things up with specialization, but look at the average response to that. No, clearly the attitude is ...
<br />
<p>
<br />
- Make every pet a monster
<br />
- Give me nukes in every resist
<br />
- Make rains have no downsides
<br />
- Remove all recast delays
<br />
- Remove all illusions
<br />
- Remove the component to every spell
<br />
- In fact, just remove all downsides to everything
<br />
- Give us snare, self evac, FD
<br />
- Give us everything else other classes have
<br />
- Make us the best soloers
<br />
- Make us the best groupers
<br />
- Make us the best raiders
<br />
- Assure me a group k plz thx n stuff !11!!!!!1!!
<br />
<p>
<br />
So if your ideas go against those basic premises, they won't be too warmly received here. Don't worry though, it isn't just mages, it's most everyone that plays EQ. They don't understand that power-at-expense, and specialization is what makes games interesting and fun in the long run. They think linear block power increases make the game fun. They do, but it's tremendously fleeting. It takes all of 3 seconds to master the OoW "20% more damage nuke". Though it gives people lots of free time, which is why they rant so much on here about all the things the class sucks at.  <img src="images/smiles/eusa_eh.gif" alt="Eh?" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
